description.text:
This is a slider leveling base for use on an OpenBuilds V-Slot Gantry.

I have included two bases. The Base - Fixed keeps the hinge point fixed. I have not printed that one but it should work but will restrict the angel from going all the way to 90 degrees...

I found in testing this is adequate for mounting the camera and a light ball head. If you start adding a lot of weight it will flex... I may add a mount with a fixed rather then slot mounting location for the camera... that, with some bracing would be stiffer...

two braces are required, one for each side of the mount.

Parts :

http://openbuildspartstore.com/v-slot-gantry-plates/
10 m5 nuts (http://amzn.to/1XLLVCs)
Open Builds flat headed m5 bolts
1 1/4 20 camera screw (http://amzn.to/1XLM3Cb)

I'm going to look for thumb screws that fit without hitting the gantry plate as I don't want to have to carry an allen wrench with me...

In the photos I'm using :
Andoer Adapter Plate Square Clamp - (http://amzn.to/1VKfTsV)
Fotga Universal Quick Release Plate L Bracket - (http://amzn.to/1SnEk9C)

Printer Brand:

RepRap

Printer:

Folgertech 2020

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.3

Infill:

30

Notes:

I printed these with eSun black pete (http://amzn.to/1Qrcsz6)

this material is very stringy... for the base I used support in the channel
This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/iBM77efH7tH

This was based on Eccentric Sphere Gears (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:6499). I modified the SCAD files so that it would use pins instead of screws to secure the gears to the center piece. Also, this one is not eccentric so that the gears spin without the object changing shape. The STL files are already plated for printing (it can be done in 3 prints). Individual gears and center now added. Note you would need to print 4 of each of the large and small gears - and the 'singlepins' (spheregearPins.stl fit the plated prints only).
Printed on a Replicator.

comments.text: This is beautiful design and the finished sphere works freely and has a nice feel about it. The pins were exactly the right size, and having clipped it all together I'm not sure if I could pull it apart again - I'm not going to try! I'd suggest that this is an intermediate level build. The small gears have a very small first layer and I had trouble with them pulling free during the build. I solved this by putting tiny brims on them. It's a really cool build, and I thank you very much for posting it here :)

comments.text: We had the same problem with loose pins and the ball falling apart.  We solved the problem by reprinting the pins at 105% of original size.  Could probably have gone a little larger, maybe 106% or 107%, but it works much better.  Also need to make sure you use the longer pins in the big pieces and the shorter pins in the smaller pieces.

comments.text: I'd be curious on how you printed them - I've printed them as is in PLA and ABS and so have others without any issues (they are actually quite stable and so far have lasted months and months of constant use).  There are several others aside from me with examples of this print - including the one posted as part of this entry.  You seem to be the first who has noted any issues.  Also, the sphere DOES scale - the initial scad designs were scaled 50% to create the plates associated with this design.  Let me know if you have any queries.

title: XYZ da Vinci 1.0 E3D V6 Bowden complete conversion (no drilling, no cutting) (updated 3/8/17)

description.text:
UPDATE!

3/8/2017: I added an updated version of the hotend_base file, called "hotend_base_v2." After struggling with some part corner lifting (more than I would have thought, even with ABS) I did some flow visualization and determined that a slight amount of air was blowing across the print bed and the printed part. This air was circulating around the underside of the carriage below the rear side of the heat sink fins. The new hotend_base file shrouds the rear of the heat sink, leaving a duct for the air to escape through the original stepper motor bore hole and onto the top side of the carriage, away from the print bed. While this is an improvement in restricting airflow, it didn't make things air tight (to my eye anyway), so I wrapped the underside (between the fan duct/base of the heat sink and the hot end heat block) in a little aluminum foil, secured with some electrical tape (far from the hot parts), to make sure no air was escaping and blowing onto the print bed. I've run the printer for about 15 hours so far on three medium-large solid infill parts and it seems to have reduced some of my curling problems, even for these challenging parts.

hotend_base_v2 is a drop-in swap for the original design, so if you're already running this Bowden conversion you should be able to print the new part in 20-30 minutes and swap it out pretty easily.

I will probably redesign this entire hot end assembly at some point and post it as a new thing. It has always bothered me that the fan duct isn't securely attached to the hotend base before installation, it makes removing and reinstalling this thing pretty fiddly, and I usually feel like I need three hands to do a good job. Aside from that I intend to design a layer cooling fan mount and duct that is easily removable with thumbscrews (so you can quickly remove that extra weight and bulk when not printing PLA). I'm hoping to be able to make one that doesn't have the belt passing through it (like another design does on Thingiverse), as I think that makes installation and removal a huge PITA. I'll also put more consideration into how I vent the hot end heat sink cooling airflow, probably leaving a larger exit hole through the original stepper motor bore hole and forcing it to blow straight up.

Original summary

This is an all original design for converting an XYZ da Vinci 1.0 to use an E3D V6 1.75mm hot end and a Bowden style extruder. It does not require any drilling, bending, or other permanent modification, except you may have to draw a 12V line from the power supply to drive the stock always-on E3D V6 fan that blows over the heat sink. You should be able to install this mod without removing the carriage, cutting up any plastic panels, or anything similarly inconvenient. Note that this mod will require you to run another firmware like Repetier, as it will require you to reverse the extrusion axis direction (easy to change in the Repetier configuration header file). The hardware side of the mod is completely reversible, although I don't personally know of a way to reflash the stock da Vinci firmware if you decided you wanted to go all the way back.

I designed this to be made of mostly small parts that are easier to print successfully on a marginal setup (like my da Vinci with the stock extruder and clog-prone hotend). The only real challenging part to print is the main extruder mount chassis, which has three areas requiring supports and a fairly long footprint that can be prone to lifting. Because a lot of these parts are under considerable compressive stress when assembled, I suggest printing this with a very high infill percentage. A sparse infill can lead to internal wall buckling that'll make the part fail. I printed mine as solid infill, as I do with any serious structural part.

This mod would technically work in a da Vinci 1.0a, but the 1.0a has holes drilled for a dual Bowden extruder mount on the top shelf of the chassis. You could do a more compact build by using the other Bowden extruder mount on Thingiverse (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:846434). Despite the title that user posted, I believe his printer is actually a da Vinci 1.0A. Mine is a vanilla 1.0 and I do not have the holes for dual extruders drilled in the chassis, just a single center placed hole used as a cable mount in the stock design.

You may be interested in the E3D V6 hotend mount even if you're using a commercial Bowden extruder with another mounting method. Reusing the stock carriage without modification has several advantages. First, you won't have to attempt printing a gigantic carriage on an ailing da Vinci stock hotend. Secondly, the stock carriage is injection molded and has a far greater strength to weight ratio of anything you could ever print on your stock printer. Additionally, the envelope of the mount and stock carriage is such that you won't have problems with the carriage crashing into the Z axis rods or other obstacles in the build area. And finally, it's always nice to know you can go back to some degree if you change your mind. I can completely revert to the original hotend configuration in about 10 minutes with a few basic tools without even removing the carriage from the printer.

I see this design as pretty basic and straightforward, but I'm pretty happy with the results. Having the extruder output a little further forward lets me run a slightly shorter Bowden tube than I would otherwise, which generally improves print quality, all other things being equal. I'm currently running my infills at 80mm/s without issue, and I could probably go faster but the printer gets super loud, so I tend to run it on the slower side. I'm glad to not hear my printer sound like it's shaking itself to death doing infills on narrow regions, slinging that stepper motor around is a serious problem in cases like that.

As usual, use this design at your own risk, I am not responsible for any damages or injuries that may result from using these parts.

Printer:

XYZ da Vinci 1.0, borosilicate bed

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2mm vertical

Infill:

100% (solid)

Parts list--------------------

Big stuff:

-1x Stock XYZ Da Vinci 1.0
-1x E3D V6 1.75mm universal Bowden kit w/ PTFE Bowden tube and screw-in extruder-end quick connect coupler. (i.e. http://www.amazon.com/E3D-All-metal-HotEnd-1-75mm-Universal/dp/B00NAK9L6Q)

Fasteners:

I used mostly metric but also a few SAE fasteners (the plastic thread cutting screws) because I live in the United States, and a much wider variety of SAE fasteners are available to me locally. You can substitute with suitable metric fasteners if you're not in the US, and re-form the holes from the STEP file to suit what you have available.

Aside from the brass heat set threaded inserts, the rest of the fasteners below may be available at your local hardware store (I found most of it at my local Ace Hardware). I used these threaded inserts because I had them on hand from previous builds, and in my experience they are superior to captive nuts in that they distribute stress throughout the surrounding material rather than as a concentrated shear stress at the edges of the nut face and floor of the hex cutout. I always keep some on hand. You should be able to modify the part from the STEP files to accommodate captive nuts if you wish, but give these heat set inserts a try if you're ever ordering a bunch of stuff from McMaster-Carr -- they're great for higher stress applications! Note that you need a soldering iron with a medium tapered/fine tip to install these. You can find instructional videos on YouTube

I put McMaster-Carr part numbers for all the fasteners in the design. I'm not suggesting you go out and buy every single item (they only come in 25-50 packs usually, and at a high price), but they'll give you an idea what you should be looking for (length, maybe head style, etc).

Bowden extruder:
-3x M3 brass heat set threaded insert for plastic (McMaster No. 94180A331)
-8x M3 washer (i.e. McMaster No. 90965A130)
-1x M3x25mm socket cap machine screw (i.e. McMaster No. 91292A020)
-4x M3x30mm socket cap machine screw (i.e. McMaster No. 91292A022)
-2x M3x35mm socket cap machine screw (i.e. McMaster No. 91292A033)

Hotend mount:
-6x M3 brass heat set threaded insert for plastic (McMaster No. 94180A331)
-6x M3 washer (i.e. McMaster No. 90965A130)
-4x M3x16mm phillips machine screw (i.e. McMaster No. 92005A126)
-2x M3x25mm phillips machine screw (i.e. McMaster No. 92005A130)
-2x #4-20x0.625 thread forming screw for plastic (i.e. McMaster No. 99461A140)
-2x #4x0.5 thread forming screw for brittle plastic (i.e. McMaster No. 97975A115)
-2x #4 plastic washer 0.25" outer diam (i.e. McMaster No. 90295A045)
-4x #6 washer (i.e. McMaster No. 90107A007)

Notes-------------------------
Hopefully the pictures have been sufficient, but here are a few things that may not be readily apparent:

Extruder assembly notes:
-There needs to be an M3 washer above the swivel joint on the extruder idler arm. It's shown in one of the photos, but this is very important as it lets the idler arm rotate freely and if you forget it you could crack the chassis when you tighten down the motor screws.
-The thumbscrews are designed to have the screws epoxied into them (i.e. JB Weld, Devcon, etc). I do this because the thumbscrews make assembly much easier, but if you follow suit you should make sure to leave the socket clear of epoxy so that it can still be turned using a hex key -- use the thumbscrews to tighten it down most of the way, and the hex key to tighten the rest of the way it to keep it from moving around when you're using it.
-There is a trick to epoxying screws into thumbscrews like this so they're aligned properly. Put a layer of saran wrap over the hole the thumbscrew will go through, then push the thumbscrew and screw through it, poking a hole in the saran wrap. Screw it down moderately tight. Mix your epoxy, carefully use a toothpick to apply the epoxy between the screw head and the wall of the thumbscrew, being careful to let keep the hex socket clear. The saran wrap makes sure you don't have any epoxy leaking down to glue the thumbscrew to the rest of your parts. Being mounted in the hole lets you ensure the screw and face of the thumbscrew will be perpendicular.
-As an installation tip, put some electrical tape on the top of the metal shelf around the hole, just a strip on either side will do. The texture on the top layer of the shelf spacer will grab into the tape and prevent the extruder from rotating.
-Wrap a layer of electrical tape around the bowden tube and the bowden fitting where they go under the secondary and tertiary guide caps (if necessary). The rubberyness of the vinyl will help the caps grip the parts better than just hard ABS on PTFE/ABS.
-The spring mount hooks onto the free hanging M3x25 screw. Make sure to mount the bowden tube fitting so the hex flats are horizontal on top and bottom. It's not shown this way in the CAD assembly pictures, but it occurred to me during assembly.
-The black thing under the primary guide cap is the rubber fitting that comes stock in the da Vinci printer, it holds the little filament feed tube in the plastic support above the filament source. If you lost this, you may want to take the STEP files and fill the cutouts back in so you can just have it grab onto the PTFE bowden tube material.

Hotend assembly notes
-The clearances are pretty tight between the fan duct and the hotend cap, which is why I selected phillips head screws that are lower profile than a standard socket cap screw. I would not try to make much of a substitution here.
-I would suggest positioning the hotend as shown. The heater and thermistor cables can run up toward the back of the printer next to the fan duct, over the fan duct, then around to the thermistor ports, etc.
-The little loop on the backplate is for cable tying your wiring harness to the carriage.

Finally, here's a video of this printer in action:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dyvJHKajml8

The screws I ended up using were slightly different than my CAD assembly, I switched to some things that were available locally as individual parts I recommend orienting the extruder stepper as shown. It gives some room to coil up and tie down the excess stepper cabling Top down view. These prints were somewhat rough as my stock da Vinci hot end was on its last legs Just a quick shot showing how I chose to wire the 30mm 12V fan into my system. I chose not to cut up my wiring harness and instead soldered directly onto the hardlines coming off the sockets. The +12V and GND on the top and bottom sockets are easily accessible to soldering without having to remove anything from the system. This image shows the original design of hotend_base, note that the heatsink fins are visible. This allows cooling air to flow down onto the print bed and part. This has been corrected in hotend_base_v2 Using the new hotend_base_v2 design, I further sealed heatsink airflow using two pieces of aluminum foil. They're secured with some electrical tape further up the duct (not visible). Using the new hotend_base_v2 design, I further sealed heatsink airflow using two pieces of aluminum foil. They're secured with some electrical tape further up the duct (not visible).

comments.text: Move your nozzle to be coincident with the rear edge of your bed glass, you should see that there are no clearance issues. If you move the carriage to the rearmost extreme of the y axis (nozzle behind the print bed), then yes, technically you could force the fan to crash into the Z sensor housing, but this should not happen in use. If it happens when printing then I can think of three possibilities -- your printer is different (i.e. not a da Vinci 1.0/1.0a), you assembled it wrong, or your firmware is not stock XYZ or Repetier v0.92. I have used this mod with both firmwares and the carriage does not crash into the Z sensor housing, even when printing a large object that takes up almost the entire print area.

comments.text: I'm printing the ABS a lot hotter than I used to with the XYZ firmware and hot end, the commanded temperature at least. The genuine E3D hot end comes with a certain thermistor you can technically select in the Repetier firmware configuration.h file, but the way XYZ wired in the stock thermistor makes it so the correct setting in Repetier's firmware is inaccurate. When I set the "correct" thermistor table it was telling me the ambient temperature in my home was like 40C or something, it was way off. Some people have removed a resistor to correct this, but instead I went back to the default thermistor table in Repetier's firmware, which was pretty close. With this setting the hot end thermistor shows close to what what my true ambient temperature is. I think the output may be slightly off at higher temperatures though because I've been printing ABS at 250C for eSun red ABS, and 260C for eSun black ABS. With the XYZ firmware I was printing closer to 200C.

description.text:
My FIRST Make!
My gf is working on a play at the local elementary school. They needed a prop so I made this. Thanks to the user (Geoffro) for the the Lion Model!

Steps ( look at photos )

  1. Print file. I didn't use the gem, but supplied it. In Cura use separate objects command, Then multiply the gem if you want to use. I just went to Michael's and bought some small gems. Much easier. The gems are really small and might be hard to print.

  2. Primer it a color you want to see under the gold if you plan to make weathered.

  3. Spray it with Gold.

  4. Follow normal steps of roughening it up. Dremel tool, Sand paper. Apply some marks and paint with silver and copper paint. Keep roughening it up.

  5. Apply some clear Glaze coat. One coat will do. Let dry for 12+ hours. Afterwards roughen it up some more. Then paint over that. This gives the marks a little depth because of resin coat. Also protects your bottom coat work.

  6. Hit it with an extra light pass of gold paint. ( dont have to , but I did. ) Then give it a light glossy clear coat.

EXTRA CREDIT: See the 3 bars on the amulet? The right left and bottom? Metal or string wrap that. That was the plan with mine. I just dont have a picture of it yet.

Print each coloured thing, put together - in some cases you might to glue. Contact me, if there are questions. Didn't try it yet. I leave the single coloured parts as they are, so you can see, where to put them later on.

title: FJR1300 Body Panel with GoPro Mount

description.text:
This is a GoPro mount that replaces the body panel on the front of a 2003 Yamaha FJR1300. This is the body panel that covers the retractable windshield motor. One bolt and you can mount your GoPro without sticking anything to your bike!

Printed with PLA, normal settings standing upright with a support that I just snapped off after printing to reduce the amount of cleaning from supports. Rotate it so it prints upright and take some awesome videos grinding through the canyon!

Protective enclosure for bladeRF SDR board from http://nuand.com/. Protects the board from abuse on the desk, without blocking acess to the connectors. Since I didn't have 2.5mm screws handy, I used 2.5mm self tappers to mount the board.

Enclosure was printed in ABS on UP! 3D printer using 0.3mm layers. No additional post processing is necessary. The board is mounted in the enclosure using 2.5mm self tapping screws, however it should be easy to modify the enclosure to use screws.

comments.text: My BladeRF has the standard size USB B plug, so I had to snap off a piece of plastic.

title: Case Back for RAMPS 1.4 - No Fan!

description.text: Updated the part to fit correctly with the side panels! This is a modifications of http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:32737. I've removed the 40 mm fan holes from the back panel because I need to put the fan on the lid instead. I've also added two stiffeners on each side to help locate the side panels. The first box I printed was glued together, and the lack of stiffeners left the corners weak.

description.text:
I use FPV goggles without a built in RX so I've always just zip tied my boscam RX to a 1/2" dowel to get it up in the air. But that was clunky and tended to fall apart.

So I took a few minutes and tossed this together in OpenSCAD, then took a few more minutes to add the ability to add custom text on the front.

If there's interest I could tweak the design so the mount is customizable as well allowing different sized/shaped dowels to be used, this just happened to be what fit my needs.

It fits my RX very snugly, it doesn't come out without a bit of a fight. You may want to tweak the sizes in the rc305 module slightly if it's too tight for your RX. I've included the OpenSCAD source so that's easy to do.

Printer Brand:

RepRap

Printer:

FolgerTech 2020 Prusa i3

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.24mm

Infill:

10%

Notes:

Doesn't need much infill, the wall around the RX prints basically solid but the bit around the dowel has some infill to it.

I did print with supports so I could print it upright. Text still prints well even though it's not supported. You could edit the scad to drop the mount down even with the build plate and print without supports, but I liked the look of it like this and the support was easy to deal with.

comments.author: supernielsen

comments.text: Fits like a glove in both my genuine and knock-off titan.  A little 2mm id tubing through the hole and it's perfect! Very nice!
comments.author: mpkennedy23

comments.text: Yeah I like to see a specific 1.75 version of this..aka 2mm diameter hole... great stuff though man!
comments.author: Telli

comments.text: the inner hole its to big and large for flexible, can unpload one with 2mm diameter?
comments.author: jorgeneo560

comments.text:
Nice adatper, thanks!
Is for 3mm or 1.75mm filament size?
If you possible make a version for 1.75mm, thnaks!
comments.author: Marco67

comments.text: It'll work with 3mm, just need the proper size push-fit connector. The BSP threads are standard. The PTFE won't go all the way threw, but on 3mm Titan adapter thing it doesn't anyway.
comments.author: Marco67

comments.text: I have a smaller push fit bowden tube adapter apparently that is far too small to screw into this hole. do you know if there's another standard size that i likely have? also, is it possible you could make a version with a smaller screw thread for this size?
comments.author: a2971549

comments.text: OK I'm dumb. What's a bsp?
comments.author: shaiss

comments.text: British Standard Pipe. It's a thread standard used by most of the push fittings we use for Bowden tubes.
comments.author: shaiss

This is an updated version of the previous one I created which had too small of an opening, and too direct onto the nozzle. In addition the previous version had about 1mm tolerance off which caused it to dip a little bit touching the build plate slightly. This is bad. Even though performance of it was decent.
This new version is Much tighter tolerances. Hovers just over the buildplate, rock solid, bigger airflow nozzle pointed more downwards. (and to the other side as well)
Works with STOCK ultimakers, doesn't interfere with blocks, uses all standard parts. V2 hothead.

Simply print without supports.
No special instructions.
Use standard ultimaker bolts to bolt fan onto shroud (you only need 2)
slide shroud onto the long bolts it should fit snuggly.
Use standard nuts to fasten onto long bolts
Check to see that it doesn't hit your print bed when zeroed.

Made this 13T RC Car Pulley as a temporary fix while I waited for aluminum ones, it worked fine for a just as long as the original plastic ones.  
(In my photo the green one is printed and the black is stock)  
Its basically a replica of the stock plastic pulley from my Sakura D3 CS drift car - but should work for any 1:10 RC situation, has a whole for a pin to the shaft.  
--  
Edit: I made 12, 14 & 15 teeth pulleys and also added my c4d file, you can edit the # in the rectangle array to add teeth. sorry, im not cad guy :\
.10mm, 100% infill

description.text: I own a Toyota RAV4 and there isn't a convenient place to put parking garage tickets so I made this to slide over the back of the visor as a light clamp to hold the parking ticket. The RAV sun visor is 19mm thick.

Printer:

Cocoon Create

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.25mm

Infill:

20%

Notes:

I printed this with a 0.8mm thickness as it needs to clamp the visor and not bend open. I used a 20 line brim to anchor it while printing.

remixed_from.title: Gadgets3D LCD mount for Prusa i3

title: LCD GADGETS3D mount for prusa i3 aluminium frame

description.text:
This is a GADGETS3D LCD panel holder for the prusa i3 aluminium frame.
The kit mounts with left top part of the z axis. You don't need to make holes, just chages your current screws with other longer ones.
It rotates 95 degrees. You need:
8 nuts M3
6 screws M3x20 or 2 screws M3x20 and 4 screws M3x16
The kit mounts with left top part of the z axis. You don't need to make holes, just chages your current screws with other longer ones.

comments.text: Great design, worked really well.  I recommend that anyone who makes this with PLA use a pretty high fill density.  I used 60% and the joints were too brittle; one of them broke with very little force while I was screwing it together.
comments.author: matheda

comments.text: Nice design. Also a perfect fit for a Prusa Air 2.

RHD is for motor on right of printer when facing the printer
LHD is for motor on left of printer .......... All model files have been run through netfab online

I've just made som simple station signs for LGB-station houses (Pola, Vollmer, Piko etc). The font is called "Alte schwabacher". Print them in black, paint them white and then sand them off until the text and border shows again.

On request others can easily be made (with any font).

This project came about because I wanted some shelf mounted lights in my projector room.

To facilitate this, I bought some Ikea Dioders, and while these work great, the light bleeds out from the shelves on to the projector screen which wasn't the effect I was looking for.

To work around this, I simply cut an A4 sheet of paper in half, folded the halves down the middle and balanced them on the shelves above, thus blocking the light a little.

I had long since considered using a 3D printer to replace these, but having 12 of these strips at 30cm long, I considered this a massive waste of filament.

A friend of mine suggested using aluminium U channel rods which you can get very easily at most hardware stores (I got mine in Brico here in Antwerp). They're sold as 1m lengths which I cut into 3 x 33cm sections (this can be done with a Dremel and a circular saw attachment or similar).

You can get these in various sizes, but I went for 10x13x10x1.5 mm cuts, but others are available - the model is parametric, so you can change it suit the material you have using:

http://www.geminidev.be/3d/openjscad/#examples/doodalights/

Note that you should add 0.2mm tolerance to the width/height of the rods.

To put the lights in place, I used blutack - I still have to complete it by drilling cable holes through the back of the shelves, but all in all, very happy with the results so far, and I have many other ideas for use of them (some related to lights, some not...).

title: Additional parts to Rubberband MiniBlaster from vanmunch

description.text:
Hi,
in addition to vanmunchs Rubber Band Mini Blaster (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:672654) I created a different solution cause you don't get the missing parts that easy in europe. Addiditonally to my printing parts I used:

for glueing: UHU Plast Spezial (works perfectly with ABS)
as connection for the sockets: 5mm rod ( I used aluminium)
as motor: http://www.amazon.de/3-6V-kurzer-Welle-Drehmoment-Getriebemotor/dp/B008OAYP8Q?ie=UTF8&psc=1&redirect=true&ref_=oh_aui_detailpage_o08_s00
a battery holder just like this http://www.amazon.de/10er-Set-Batteriehalter-Mignon-Druckknopfanschlu%C3%9F/dp/B00X4R2AYU?ie=UTF8&psc=1&redirect=true&ref_=oh_aui_detailpage_o04_s00 , but since there is not enough space in the body you'll have to cut of the holding wings of the holder and just tape the batteries in: http://www.amazon.de/10er-Set-Batteriehalter-Mignon-Druckknopfanschlu%C3%9F/dp/B00X4R2AYU?ie=UTF8&psc=1&redirect=true&ref_=oh_aui_detailpage_o04_s00
as button is used: http://www.amazon.de/SODIAL-5er-momentanen-Armaturenbrett-aus/dp/B00HUHBV40?ie=UTF8&psc=1&redirect=true&ref_=oh_aui_detailpage_o03_s00

as motor connection: M3x10 screw with M3 nut (you will need to add a drilling for the screw, as you can see in the picture).
to connect the motor to the body you'll have to cut out some of Top body
to connect the cover to the body I added two short 3mm bolts and made a 2,5mm drilling to ensure that the bolts are not loose. I know the cover is much bigger, but otherwise you don't get 4 batteries in. I also think that with this solution your fingers get less easy involved with the spindal.
the cord holder is just glued to the body as you can see in the picture.
I added another spindal cause the motor I used was not strong enough for a 90mm spindel, but I couldn't find a stronger one for 6V.
As cord I used a nylon cord for the string serving (archery)

I asked vanmunch for permission to this, but I also strongly recommend that you use his shop to get the additional parts.

Have fun
NinjaQ

title: Flash tilt insert for B.I.G. Helios kombi schirmhalter

description.text:
I have bought head for photographic flash umbrella which works fine, but has one big construction error. 
The umbrella stake hole in the head is parallel with the flash reflector direction. As the reflector is usually located on the highest place of the flash unit, it is off umbrella axis so the flash is not shining uniformly to the umbrella. The solution is to tilt the flash unit so, that the reflector is shining to the center of umbrella. 
So I created semiparametric SDAD file for the tilt insert. I'm using tilt angle of 8 deg for my Nikon SB800 flash (the generated STL file is for that angle), but you can change that parameter to suit your type of the flash. The higher is the position of reflector, the bigger must be the angle.

1) Print the part.
2) Unscrew two little screws on the top of the head (you need star shaped screwdriver)
3) Remove the bar with the aditional light screw
4) Insert the part and fix the screws back

description.text:
If you’re not happy with the something, you can probably change it. Plastic surgery is a growing trend in America. People, usually women, of all ages search high and low for the best plastic surgeon available. Whether you are in the market for a new set of lips, a new nose, cheekbones, butt or whatever- it’s available. The file I created is based off of a Mr. Potato head set, where the user is allowed to put in the features they want. Instead of more cartoonish facial features I tried to go for something a little more realistic to mimic the selection of choosing different features with plastic surgery. This object is a wearable, allowing the user to perhaps “try out” different looks if he or she so desires. The product is designed in order to look like each facial feature looks good on their own, but when formed together on the face begins to look “ugly”. This is because like real plastic surgery, on their own, one surgery is fine. However when you pile a bunch on top the real problem occurs.The “ugliness” is so that the wearer can understand, that plastic surgery doesn’t “fix” or enhance anything. Usually, people who get plastic surgery, especially multiple surgeries end up looking “plastic” or unrealistic.
Or..just use it as a creepy mask.

description.text:
The [logger] is my year project. It helps young people to understand physical experiments a more easily way, but also with exact measurements. These experiments for example, measuring the velocity and the acceleration of a rolling ball on a gradient, or the same with a horizontally accelerated object. But you also can measure the friction on of an accelerated object on various surfaces. The physical elements of the project mostly been printed with 3D printer, but I always payed attention to use a universal materials. This project is completely open source, anyone can access and download the individual models and can print out them, build them. It works with a Nodemcu, and was programmed in Arduino.
Other infos: http://simi.hu/logger/

I made a simple turningknob that fits on my 100kOhm variable resistors. The design is made using openscad
This is a stamp I made for my nephew to use when playing with modelling compounds such as PLAY-DOH. It's reversed so that it will show his name when stamped into the material.

This should print fine on a Makerbot or similar 3D printer, I used 100% fill and 0 extra shells. If you don't happen to know anyone named Fraser, you can make your own by following the directions at http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ABusDqKF0Dw

My first attempt at a useful thing.  I'm learning openSCAD in anticipation of receiving my printrbot+ and I thought I would make something useful.  This is a parametric pillow block.  At least I think its parametric... (still learning the ropes here) If you change the parameters at the beginning of the file you can change pretty much everything and get a nice customized pillow block.
you can even make it into a bushing by setting the "lip_size" to zero and increasing the "bearing_thickness".
Edit: version 0.2.  I fixed a mixup between diameter and radius and added some more comments.  The SCAD file is theoretically set up for a 608 skate bearing with tabs for m5 bolts.
since I am still waiting on my printrbot+, I have not printed this ... yet.

Enclosure for Peter Bartlett's MISE and M3SE.

http://bartlettlabs.com/MISE/index.html
http://bartlettlabs.com/M3SE/index.html

The source design files are the *.FCStd files, which are used with FreeCAD.
http://www.freecadweb.org/

The *.stl files are for getting 3D prints of the parts.

Source is maintained on github!
https://github.com/aljex/MISE-enclosure

Gallery:
https://goo.gl/photos/jDpvjbgjePCddrG99

Video:
https://youtu.be/Me62yHelnyM

Directions

1 - 3D print the *.stl files

Pick ONE, MISE or M3SE

MISE     M3SE
MISE_top_cover.stl M3SE_top_cover.stl
MISE_base_plate.stl MISE_base_plate.stl
MISE_cf_retainer.stl MISE_cf_retainer.stl



When you select "print" from Thingiverse and it launches 3dhubs, it will select all 4 STL files by default at first. You have to remove which ever top_cover you don't want!
MISE and M3SE both use the same cf_retainer and base_plate. The only difference is M3SE has a wider ribbon cable opening.
You could really just use the M3SE top_cover for both MISE and M3SE, but I like my own to fit perfectly, so I preserve the option for you too.

2 - Aquire the following parts

  • 1 40-pin "IDE" male-female extension cable, 4 inch length
    It needs to be an extension, with one male and one female connector.
    The direction the cable exits the connector on the male end matters. The cable should go away from the key notch in the side of the connector.
    No extra fold / strain relief clip on the male connector.
    No special requirements for the female connector.

    http://www.cablesonline.com/240pinidedir.html
    Change “Available Lengths: 4 inches FI-004”

  • 4 flat-head #8 x 3/4" sheet metal or wood screws
    I prefer stainless steel as well but that's just a preference.
    Self-tapping would be better (less likely to break the screw posts the first time the screws are run in) but those are not common at your local hardware store, and standard sheet metal screws like the examples below are fine.

    On-Line:
    https://www.boltdepot.com/Product-Details.aspx?product=2214

    Home Depot:
    http://www.homedepot.com/p/Crown-Bolt-8-x-3-4-in-Phillips-Flat-Head-Sheet-Metal-Screws-5-per-Pack-35271/202706578

    Lowes:
    http://www.lowes.com/pd_150742-37672-126965_1z0vrdvZ1z0yjldZ1z0yjpkZ1z0zbdkZ1z1291f__?productId=3817895&pl=1

  • 4 small rubber feet
    http://www.homedepot.com/p/Everbilt-1-2-in-Self-Adhesive-Vinyl-Surface-Bumpers-16-per-Pack-49967/203661150

3 - Assembly

Unplug the cf reader from the MISE.
Remove the 4 nylon stand-offs from the screw holes on the MISE.
Plug the female end of the 40 pin extension cable into the MISE where the cf reader used to be.

Use an angled pick/probe tool to clean out the two cf retainer clip slots. FDM printers generally leave junk inside those.

Lay the cf reader flat in the small tray formed into the corner of the top_cover, with the lights and jumpers up facing you. The white CF slot on the back side of the cf reader fits exactly into that tray.

Looking down into the top_cover with the cf reader in the top-left corner, insert the bent end of the retainer clip into the slot to the right of the cf reader.
Swing the retainer clip down over the cf reader, and slide the straight end into the slot to the left of the cf reader, attached to the screw post.
Push the retainer clip forward until it snaps firmly in place.
If anything seem too stiff or doesn't seem to fit, make sure those slots are really cleaned out.

Turn the top_cover around so the cf reader is to your right and close to you, and the round hole on the rear wall is away from you.
Hold the MISE upside down with the network jack away from you.
Angle the network jack down into the rear wall away from you. Rest the rear side of the MISE on the two rear screw posts, keep the front side of the MISE lifted up.
Connect the male end of the 40 pin extension cable onto the cf reader.
Lay the front edge of the MISE down, pay attention that the network jack pokes into the square hole in the rear wall as you swing the front edge down.

Press the 4 rubber feet onto the FLAT side of the base_plate, just inside of the screw holes (right next to each screw hole, towards the center of the plate rather than towards the outside edge).
Place the base_plate on top of the MISE, with the short risers down, touching the MISE (ie with the new feet up).
Make sure the screw holes line up. The screws are closer to the rear wall and further away from the front wall.
The base_plate should now be flush with the edge of the top_cover.

Install the 4 screws. Don't over-tighten. 3d-printing is not super strong.

DONE!

Notes on 3d printing

Where/how to get a print?

I used http://www.3dhubs.com to find a small local individual 3D print service.
This is both cheaper and more convenient than some of the larger internet 3d print services.
In my case the printer I found turned out to be a local R/C drone hobby shop, but it could be anything from a guy with a printer in his garage to a dedicated manufacturing shop.

But there are numerous 3D print services on-line. The most famous is probably http://www.shapeways.com

Special warning

The top_cover is very difficult to print in ABS using FDM. Because of the size and shape of the part, it tends to curl up from the bed.
I personally recommend printing in ABS anyway, for the strength and longevity of the material. It is possible to print in ABS, it just requires a good printer with a heated bed and full enclosure, and it requires the printer operator to be fairly good.
I think the main tricks being used by the guy who has successfully printed several prototypes for me are,

  • the part is elevated off the print bed and printed on rafting,
  • and the in-fill seems to be about 50% density.

Also not all colors of ABS have the same mechanical properties it seems. I have a few prints in black ABS which are fine, but when I got a print in grey ABS, it was more brittle, the layers split apart in a couple of the screw posts, and part of the exterior wall layer separated. Those were all repairable with acetone.

Another option is to print in PLA instead. PLA will print a lot easier. The downside of PLA is that it's a biodegradable material made from corn. That matters for this particular thing, because it's used with vintage computers which hopefully will be preserved another 30 years just like how they are 30 years old already today. Well who knows how well PLA will have held up over the course of 30 years of inconsistent care and storage. It might not be very nice for the niece or nephew or grandkids who gets your collection of vintage stuff in 30 years. It's also more brittle. But even so, it's probably fine for this part. On the plus side, since the source files are public, someone in the future could just print a new copy even easier and cheaper and better than today.

Another option is to print by some other method than FDM. For instance, http://www.shapeways.com prints by laser sintering, not FDM, and their cheapest material is nylon, not ABS. I have not ordered a print of this from Shapeways (because it's $90 just for the top_cover part alone) but I believe it would come out perfect. But then again, nylon is awful material to try to sand and paint, or glue.

If you do print in ABS, and anything breaks, at least it's easy to repair with acetone.

When printing the top_cover using FDM printing, you definitely want to print the part with the top down, the way it appears in the freecad and stl files. Otherwise the rafting is impossible to clean out of the inside and especially it wrecks all the small exact shapes that make up the cf card reader holder in the top_cover.

Picking out the rafting

I suggest getting a "pick and probe" set to clean out the rafting from around the small features of the cf card reader holder.

Example: http://www.homedepot.com/p/Husky-Precision-Pick-and-Probe-Set-4-Piece-60004H/204314893

It's the only way to cleanly dig out the little slots for the cf retainer. You want to poke the probe points right up into all 4 corners of those slots and scrape all 5 interior surfaces to get a good clean rectangular shape inside, so the matching tab fits in.

Also pay attention to the underside of the little tabs that stick out of the front wall, between the joystick port and the cf card port. Some rafting will likely be stuck under there and it will interfere with the cf retainer which needs to snap into that spot. Scrape all along that edge actually, not just the two tabs that stick out. There is a slight overhang all along the joystick port, and you can't directly see if anything is in there to interfere with the cf retainer.

Acetone vapor finishing

In the case of ABS, I have not tried the actetone vapor trick to smooth out the surface finish. I don't know if it would melt the CF card reader holder slots and make the cf retainer clip no longer fit in the slots. If you want to try it, maybe you can do it with the cf retainer clip installed. This will almost certainly "weld" the cf retainer in place, but probably only very lightly from a very thin surface shell like paint. You can probably just break the part out and then the part would work normally. The point would be that the cf retainer clip would be filling the slots and therefore the slots wouldn't melt in and close up.

Or maybe you just scrape out the slots with the picks after doing the acetone vapor.

Or maybe it's just not a problem in the first place.

Painting

The closest off-the-shelf paint match I've found so far is:
Dupli-Color Bumper Coating FB108 Medium Silver.
http://www.amazon.com/Dupli-Color-FB108-Medium-Flexible-Coating/dp/B00296DXN4

It's not an exact match, but very close from a foot away. Up real close you can tell these differences:

  • It's slightly more matte or satin than the TRS-80.
  • The grain of the metallic particulate making up the silver is slightly larger/coarser than the TRS-80.

There is probably a more accurate match out there somewhere, I just haven't found it yet. So if you find it, let everyone else know!

You could probably get a very very good match by taking a sample to an autobody shop and have them mix up a custom batch.

Hackers of the world, your storage problems are over! I give you the toilet roll drawer. Print one in under an hour, and in due time, all your little stuff can be neatly stored

The design files can be further tweaked for better printing. I might do that in due time. For my needs they suffice. If you open in customizer, give a layer_th value of a multiple of your printed layers. Don't give a value more than 0.4 for ABS, or you will no longer be able to bend the base. The drawer has not been tested for other toilet roll sizes, if errors in the script, give a ping. Idea for the bending is from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:33765

Hand out an ID tag with promotional information (about your hackerspace website for instance) when demonstrating your 3D printer. Sometimes it is difficult to come up with a trinket to give away when demonstrating a 3D printer. This little luggage tag can identify your thumb-drive or laptop. It prints on a Printrbot LC in less than 12 minutes so it makes a good demonstration. I print up a bunch ahead of time and have them ready to hand out while people learn how 3D printers work by watching it print a tag like ones they will take home. This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://tinkercad.com/things/a6nnfVptebD

• Print Avery 5160 labels on an inkjet printer with information about your hackerspace.
    -Using the tag insert as a template you can cut the appropriate portion of a business card from the visitor with a pair of scissors and stick the hackerspace label on the back while they watch the printer.
    -Use a previously labeled piece of index card for the name and address if the visitor does not have a business card.
    -Attach a rubber band.
    -Weld the edge of the insert with a dab of super glue or with a 3Doodler if you have one.

Simple wall-mounted holder for Disney Infinity figures. The wall bracket uses a small command strip to adhere to the wall, and the figure bracket slides down onto it.

UPDATE - 5/17/16 - Removed the original wall mount and replaced with a better fitting V2. V2 mount has small ledge at the bottom of the wall mount to help stabilize the platform and account for the thickness of the command strip.

Additionally, there is a single piece version of the mount available.
